    description: `Khud Dar Imam (Imam Ahmad Bin Hanbal) is a comprehensive Urdu-language biography of Imam Ahmad bin Hanbal, may Allah have mercy on him, one of the most revered scholars, theologians, and jurists in the history of Islam and the founder of the Hanbali school of Islamic jurisprudence. The title "Khud Dar Imam" suggests the subject's unwavering resolve and steadfastness, qualities for which Imam Ahmad bin Hanbal is particularly famous in Islamic history, especially during the ordeal of the Mihnah (the inquisition) when he stood alone against the ruling caliph's attempt to impose a doctrinal position that contradicted the orthodox Islamic belief. The book provides a detailed and well-researched account of Imam Ahmad's life from his birth in Baghdad in 164 AH (780 CE) through his upbringing, education, scholarly career, trials, and eventual passing in 241 AH (855 CE). The early chapters cover Imam Ahmad's childhood, including the early loss of his father, the piety and dedication of his mother who raised him, and the beginning of his remarkable journey in the pursuit of Islamic knowledge. The book details his extensive travels across the Muslim world to study under the greatest scholars of his time, including his studies in Kufa, Basra, Makkah, Madinah, Yemen, and Syria, where he collected hadith narrations and learned fiqh from the leading authorities of each region. The author meticulously documents the vast number of scholars from whom Imam Ahmad narrated hadith, estimated at over two hundred and eighty teachers, and the equally impressive number of students who narrated from him, reflecting his central position in the chain of Islamic knowledge transmission. The book covers Imam Ahmad's methodology in hadith, his criteria for accepting and rejecting narrations, and his approach to deriving legal rulings from the primary sources of Islam. His famous work, the Musnad, one of the largest and most important hadith collections in existence, is discussed in detail, including its compilation methodology, its organisational structure, and its significance in the hadith literature. The defining episode of Imam Ahmad's life, the Mihnah, receives extensive coverage. The book narrates how the Abbasid Caliph Al-Ma'mun, influenced by the Mu'tazilite theological school, attempted to compel scholars to accept the doctrine of the createdness of the Quran. While most scholars capitulated under threat of imprisonment and punishment, Imam Ahmad bin Hanbal refused to compromise his belief, enduring years of imprisonment, flogging, and hardship with extraordinary patience and conviction. His steadfastness during this trial became one of the most celebrated episodes in Islamic history and ultimately led to the triumph of orthodox Sunni theology over Mu'tazilite influence. The book concludes with an assessment of Imam Ahmad's legacy and the lasting impact of the Hanbali school of jurisprudence on Islamic law and theology. Written in scholarly yet accessible Urdu, this biography is essential reading for anyone interested in Islamic scholarship and the lives of the great Imams.`,
